{"author":{"id":"d8a5b529a831fe2ec3072b9f42af5df35676335e5b3f40d4c21a731599abdf53"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1772289087,"nonce":"425gv0j31aZia4+8p1Z+mBKIViI=","message":"The issue does seem to be caused by `onActivated`.\n\nThe root cause is either a race condition on the extnesion side, or `port.postMessage` not respecting\nthe invocation order.\n\nOn the extension side, adding a few `console.log` statements, we see this\n\n```\nActivating 13   background.js:87:13\nRemoving 13     background.js:92:13\n```\n\nThe native host sees a different order\n\n```\n{\"action\":\"remove\",\"tab_id\":13}\n{\"window_id\":1,\"action\":\"update\",\"tab_id\":14}\n{\"action\":\"update\",\"tab_id\":13}\n```\n\nThe last \"update\" message, with only \"tab_id\", can only be produced by the `onActivated` event, which\npasses `force=true`. The `onUpdated` event skips the message if it's empty.\n\nThe native host is reading from stdin, single threaded, and the log statement is in `read_tab_info`,\nso the data *must* be written out of order by the extension.","files":null}]}